     <font class="TallRed">Death by heatstroke<a name="108761329552875524">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          <b>In which Cless embarks on a foolish journey that nearly kills him</b><br /><br />Okay, so here's my story of stupidity for you all to laugh at. A few days ago I decided to go to a local demonstration of Apple's new pro lineup of video softwareâ€”Final Cut Pro HD, Motion, DVD Studio Pro 3, and Shake 3.5. I was really excited about this, since I'd be going with my friend Anthony from JMU, a fellow SMAD major and DV junkie. He was supposed to come pick me up from work at 9AM, drive me to the Metro, we'd go to Arlington and check this place out, then go hang with a friend and have some lunch, then head back.<br /><br />Flash forward to Thursday morning. I'm sitting in my office at 9:00AM, having been there for a half hour, and Anthony hasn't called. I'm a little nervous, but wait until about 9:15. Still no call, so I go outside to wait. It's 9:22 or so now, and I'm afraid he isn't coming. So, I decide to hoof it from my office to the Vienna Metro station, because I REALLY want to go. Problem: I'm wearing a sweater and pants, because it's cold in my office (and always cold in movie theaters, which is where the demo was being held).<br /><br />I'm about a third of the way there and I'm already sweating nicely; it's very muggy and hot out. I'm not making good time, and suddenly the Metro station seems very far away. But I push through it. I get to the intersection of Lee Highway and Nutley, now soaked in sweat (and seemingly unable to sweat anymore). But the goal's just around the bend. It's pushing 10, so I'll be late already, but at least I'll get there.<br /><br />Then I get lost. I know, it seems ridiculous, but I took a wrong turn, got into a housing development and couldn't figure out where to go from there. By this point I'm definitely not actively sweating anymore, and my legs are quite tired. I decide to turn around and go to the nearest office building to try and get some directions. I get there, and ask a guy how to get there. He gives me some patently unhelpful directions and then leaves. I try to find the Metro again. 20 minutes later, I'm back at the same building, feeling faint, disoriented, and dizzy. My feet REALLY hurt at this point. I ask a lady outside for some help. She tells me to sit down and gives my dumb ass a bottle of water. This woman is, obviously, a saint.<br /><br />A commuter bus shows up and takes me to the Metro station, which is what I should've done in the first place. It's now 10:30. I've missed a half hour of the event, and will miss another 20 or so in transit. By the time I get there, it's 10 of 11. I'm already shaking my head in mild disgust, questioning my own sanity.<br /><br />Turns out they started a half hour late, so I'd only missed 20 minutes of introduction and Final Cut Pro (which I'm most familiar with). Found Anthony during an intermission. They skipped the Shake demo at the end due to lack of time, which caused me to kill everyone in the room and steal me a G5. Just kidding. But it did bother me a lot, since that's what I was most interested in. Looks like it's time to buy the training book w/ the 30-day-trial.<br /><br />And after all that, when Anthony and I compared timings, it seems I left my office JUST before he called, and left the parking lot JUST before he arrived. All this headache could've been avoided if I'd been that much more patient.<br /><br />So there you go; that's how I almost killed myself in the summer heat. Moral: if you're a geek, never go outside unless ABSOLUTELY NECESSARY and you're equipped for the environment. Otherwise, you'll die, or at least suffer exhaustion and a severe injury to your pride.<br />
