     <font class="TallRed">music, recording integrity, etc.<a name="108753296103049982">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
             Cless, I'm a bit confused here.  You wrote in your last post that, "(Tuuk's) assertion that someone in their home can record music at higher quality than most professional studio albums of the past is wishful thinking," but the 24-bit, 192 kHz recording you take note of a few sentences later is a modern standard of quality.  What Tuuk was referring to in terms of recording quality, I believe, were "most of the greatest albums of all time," which can most widely be considered to have not all been "modern" albums.<br /><br />   I guess what I'm saying is, that while the analog productions of thirty years ago may be superior to most digtital home studios of today, your post really didn't support that particular argument with fact... but, I might just be reading it wrong. <br /><br />   Anyway, I had a Recording Technology professor who vastly prefers the quality of analog to digital recordings... he always likes to remind everyone in this computer-studio age of the excellece of integrity that comes with recording on a big-ole 1-inch 16-track reel at 32 IPS and that sort of thing.  But regardless of which will win in the battle of digital versus analog, I find that either will suit me just fine.  The reason is simple: both high-quality analog and high-quality digital recordings are too good for whatever CD player or what-have-you that I can afford to play my music on.  Could I hear a difference on awesome speakers?  Probably.  But do I have those speakers?  No.  Why don't I have those speakers?  Because I'm a goddam poor musician, that's why.<br /><br />   Maybe I've gotten a little of topic, but I think the new moral of this story is: if you like music, don't be a musician.  It's bad for your ability to wallet, as well as your overall ability to enjoy most music.<br /><br />- the Kobold!<br />
